          "body": "The chapter's material register is not decorative — it is theological. Moving from outside to inside, from the porpoise-skin outermost covering (36:19) through goat-hair curtains (36:14-18) to the fine linen inner curtains woven with cherubim (36:8-13), and from the bronze entrance-pillar bases (36:38) through silver frame sockets (36:24, 26, 30) to the gold-clasped inner curtains and gold-overlaid boards (36:13, 34, 36), every material transition marks a degree of increasing holiness. The tabernacle is not a uniform sacred space; it is a gradient, with the most precious materials concentrated at the inner veil (36:35-36) — the boundary of the Holy of Holies. God's holiness is not accessible to all at equal intensity. The architectural grammar of Exodus 36 encodes what the Epistle to the Hebrews will articulate theologically: the old covenant mediated God's presence through layers of restriction, and those restrictions were not arbitrary but revelatory — they announced that the way into the Holy of Holies was 'not yet disclosed' (Hebrews 9:8) until Christ tore the veil with His flesh (Hebrews 10:20)."
